<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n15070a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n15" href="#n15070a">N15 (VI.D.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n15all.htm#n15070a"> 70(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> took away fear / brought in falsehood</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">He <font color="green">[Varro]</font> adds&mdash;and the comment is curiously one-sided and thoroughly Roman: &ldquo;those who introduced representation among the nations, <mark>took away fear and brought in falsehood</mark>.&rdquo; It was undeniably one supreme merit of the Greeks that from religion they took away fear. To the purely practical man the iconist is apt to seem a liar. <small> J.E. Harrison, <a name="MYTH1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#MYTH1"><cite title="source">Mythology</cite></a> (1924) xvi</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c15246a" href="c15all.htm#c15246a">VI.C.15:246(a)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
